And this is our chef, Arnold.

289
00:15:13,702 --> 00:15:16,412
His kind of cooking never goes out of style.

290
00:15:16,496 --> 00:15:18,581
Do you like kidney pie?

291
00:15:18,665 --> 00:15:20,458
Are you kidding me? I love it.

292
00:15:20,542 --> 00:15:21,751
ln fact, I'm a donor.

293
00:15:21,835 --> 00:15:23,169
(LAUGHING)

294
00:15:24,588 --> 00:15:26,172
I filled out the card and. . .

295
00:15:26,924 --> 00:15:29,550
No, I've never actually had that,
but I would love to try it.

296
00:15:29,676 --> 00:15:31,344
Let's have a seat.

297
00:15:32,346 --> 00:15:33,804
MAN: All right, guys. Back to work.

298
00:15:33,889 --> 00:15:39,101
I wonder if we could sit
more in the center of the room.

299
00:15:39,186 --> 00:15:41,020
I want to get a real sense of the space.

300
00:15:47,152 --> 00:15:48,402
(COOING)

301
00:15:52,032 --> 00:15:54,951
You have a very unusual name, Mr. Popper.

302
00:15:55,035 --> 00:15:56,243
And I never forget one.

303
00:15:56,578 --> 00:16:00,456
This restaurant has been in my family
for three generations.

304
00:16:00,540 --> 00:16:03,960
My grandmother served coq au vin
for Winston Churchill.

305
00:16:04,044 --> 00:16:07,254
And my father poured champagne
for Fred Astaire.

306
00:16:07,547 --> 00:16:10,800
My mother made a BLT
for Kareem Abdul-Jabbar once.

307
00:16:10,884 --> 00:16:13,135
She said he was
surprisingly down-to-earth,

308
00:16:13,220 --> 00:16:16,722
which is ironic, considering how tall he is.

309
00:16:17,182 --> 00:16:20,935
Fascinating.
But I can't sell this place to just anyone.

310
00:16:21,019 --> 00:16:24,146
I mean,
I consider the staff to be family, too.

311
00:16:24,314 --> 00:16:26,732
Nothing is more important
than family to me. Nothing.

312
00:16:27,067 --> 00:16:28,234
Are you married?

313
00:16:28,902 --> 00:16:30,403
Not presently.

314
00:16:31,363 --> 00:16:32,446
Any children?

315
00:16:32,990 --> 00:16:37,034
Two. And we have the most magical

316
00:16:37,119 --> 00:16:38,577
alternate weekends together.

317
00:16:39,162 --> 00:16:41,205
Tell me about your father.

318
00:16:41,790 --> 00:16:43,165
My father?

319
00:16:43,959 --> 00:16:45,167
Uh. . .

320
00:16:45,377 --> 00:16:47,044
What can I say?

321
00:16:47,129 --> 00:16:50,131
A father is a father.
And he was no different.

322
00:16:50,215 --> 00:16:51,549
You were close?

323
00:16:52,092 --> 00:16:56,512
Yes. Well, we're related.

324
00:16:56,596 --> 00:17:00,016
