That's good counting, Billy.

513
00:26:33,256 --> 00:26:34,256
Do they have names?

514
00:26:34,340 --> 00:26:35,841
Yeah, course.

515
00:26:37,093 --> 00:26:38,844
This one is Captain.

516
00:26:38,970 --> 00:26:40,095
(HONKS)

517
00:26:40,471 --> 00:26:41,680
Captain Popper.

518
00:26:42,181 --> 00:26:43,181
(HONKING LOUDLY)

519
00:26:43,266 --> 00:26:45,684
And that's Loudy.

520
00:26:47,270 --> 00:26:48,478
Hey! Hey!

521
00:26:48,563 --> 00:26:51,231
And that one's Bitey.

522
00:26:52,525 --> 00:26:54,026
-(FARTING)
-(GROANS) Oh !

523
00:26:54,611 --> 00:26:55,819
Stinky.

524
00:26:56,779 --> 00:26:59,197
AMANDA: Aw! He loves me.

525
00:26:59,699 --> 00:27:01,533
That's Lovey.

526
00:27:01,701 --> 00:27:03,327
-(REPLIES IN FRENCH)
-Yeah.

527
00:27:03,703 --> 00:27:04,786
(THUDDING)

528
00:27:10,668 --> 00:27:12,502
And that's Nimrod.

529
00:27:12,879 --> 00:27:14,463
Let's make a fort.

530
00:27:14,631 --> 00:27:17,132
-Oh ! Fort! Cool.
-Go.

531
00:27:17,216 --> 00:27:18,884
Billy, the cushions. . .

532
00:27:19,010 --> 00:27:21,428
That's a great idea for fort building.

533
00:27:21,512 --> 00:27:22,554
AMANDA: I've got to tell you,

534
00:27:22,639 --> 00:27:26,224
you have officially raised the
birthday present bar to a whole new level.

535
00:27:26,309 --> 00:27:28,977
-I know!
-How did you find them, anyway?

536
00:27:29,062 --> 00:27:32,230
Some sort of, I don't know,
birthday-penguin rental company?

537
00:27:32,315 --> 00:27:33,357
Um. . .

538
00:27:33,441 --> 00:27:36,193
No. Actually, Thom Sr.

539
00:27:38,154 --> 00:27:40,822
-Your dad?
-Yeah.

540
00:27:40,907 --> 00:27:43,325
Wait. You saw him? How is he?

541
00:27:43,409 --> 00:27:44,576
He passed away.

542
00:27:45,244 --> 00:27:46,453
As in, he's dead?

543
00:27:46,579 --> 00:27:49,164
Yeah. He broke on through
to the other side.

544
00:27:49,248 --> 00:27:51,500
Oh, my God. I'm. . .

545
00:27:51,584 --> 00:27:53,543
I'm so sorry.

546
00:27:53,628 --> 00:27:57,089
-Are you okay?
-Yeah, I'm fine.

547
00:27:57,173 --> 00:27:58,590
You're fine.

548
00:27:58,883 --> 00:28:00,592
Fine. I'm good.

549
00:28:00,677 --> 00:28:02,052
-(EXHALES)
-And he left me those.

550
00:28:02,136 --> 00:28:05,138
Hey, where're you going? Come back here.

551
00:28:06,224 --> 00:28:07,933
-Got you !
-Hey! (LAUGHS)

552
00:28:09,769 --> 00:28:11,186
You look great.

553
00:28:11,270 --> 00:28:13,438
-Thanks. I should get the cake in the. . .
-That's a nice cake.

554
00:28:13,523 --> 00:28:14,606
-(CLATTERING)
-Oh !

555
00:28:14,899 --> 00:28:15,982
What?

556
00:28:18,236 --> 00:28:20,153
Oh, my God !

557
00:28:20,238 --> 00:28:21,321
How cute.

558
00:28:21,406 --> 00:28:23,281
lt looks like they're nesting.

559
00:28:23,366 --> 00:28:25,283
Finally, you have something in your fridge.

560
00:28:25,451 --> 00:28:26,618
(DOORBELL RINGING)

561
00:28:28,162 --> 00:28:29,371
-Yeah?
-Thomas Popper?

562
00:28:29,455 --> 00:28:30,622
Uh-huh.

563
00:28:30,707 --> 00:28:32,165
Nat Jones, New York Zoo.

564
00:28:33,292 --> 00:28:34,459
Flightless Bird Division.

565
00:28:34,544 --> 00:28:37,295
Your assistant called,
the one with the "P" problem.

566
00:28:37,380 --> 00:28:38,964
I'm here for the penguin.

567
00:28:39,632 --> 00:28:40,966
Wow.

568
00:28:41,050 --> 00:28:42,592
She didn't tell me they were Gentoos.

569
00:28:42,677 --> 00:28:43,844
How many do you have?

570
00:28:44,303 --> 00:28:45,387
-Five?
-Six.

571
00:28:45,471 --> 00:28:47,097
Six! Oh, God. Even better.

572
00:28:47,265 --> 00:28:48,974
-What's going on?
-It's nothing.

573
00:28:49,100 --> 00:28:53,103
I'll take care of it.
Hey, save me a piece of that. Mmm !

574
00:28:54,313 --> 00:28:56,982
I've got my team downstairs,
and a fully equipped retrieval van.

575
00:28:57,066 --> 00:28:58,066
Yeah, that's great.

576
00:28:58,151 --> 00:29:00,986
But listen, you can't actually take
the penguins right now.

577
00:29:01,112 --> 00:29:03,613
-What are you talking about?
-Believe me, I'd love to give them to you.

578
00:29:03,698 --> 00:29:05,741
But it's my kid's birthday,
and he's crazy about them.

579
00:29:05,825 --> 00:29:06,867
You know kids.

580
00:29:06,951 --> 00:29:09,327
I don't know kids. I know penguins.

581
00:29:09,412 --> 00:29:11,580
They like ice, snow and fish.

582
00:29:11,664 --> 00:29:12,789
Put them in a New York apartment,

583
00:29:12,874 --> 00:29:14,499
they're gonna get beak rash
and wing mange

584
00:29:14,584 --> 00:29:16,251
faster than you can
blow out your birthday candles.

585
00:29:16,335 --> 00:29:17,919
-Wing mange?
-It's not pretty.

586
00:29:18,004 --> 00:29:19,337
Those animals belong in a zoo.

587
00:29:19,422 --> 00:29:21,965
Hey, I get it.
I just have to take care of the politics.

588
00:29:22,049 --> 00:29:25,469
Mr. Popper, don't postpone the inevitable.
Give me the birds.

589
00:29:25,553 --> 00:29:28,764
Yeahbsolutely. They're yours.
Just not right now.

590
00:29:28,848 --> 00:29:30,682
-I'll call you. Okay.
-Yeah. Soon.

591
00:29:33,853 --> 00:29:36,104
Hey, it's me.

592
00:29:36,189 --> 00:29:39,274
He's got six of them. And they're Gentoos.

593
00:29:39,358 --> 00:29:41,151
Not yet, but I'll get them.

594
00:29:41,235 --> 00:29:42,527
BILLY: What was that?

595
00:29:42,862 --> 00:29:44,988
What did that man mean,
"I'm here for the penguins"?

596
00:29:45,406 --> 00:29:48,742
Oh, that guy?
He's here for their baths.

597
00:29:48,826 --> 00:29:51,203
He's the bather. Trust me,
you're going to want them bathed.

598
00:29:51,370 --> 00:29:53,121
I just told him to come back later,

599
00:29:53,206 --> 00:29:54,706
because we're in the middle of a part-ay!

600
00:29:54,874 --> 00:29:57,083
They're mine, right? I can keep them?

601
00:29:57,251 --> 00:29:59,753
You kidding me?
What kind of question is that?

602
00:29:59,837 --> 00:30:01,338
I don't know, Billy.

603
00:30:01,422 --> 00:30:03,131
I'd make him promise if I were you.

604
00:30:04,217 --> 00:30:05,801
Do you promise me, Popper?

605
00:30:06,594 --> 00:30:07,969
Yes.

606
00:30:08,054 --> 00:30:09,304
JANIE: Say the words.

607
00:30:09,388 --> 00:30:10,806
You don't want to disappoint them.

608
00:30:10,890 --> 00:30:12,265
When did I ever disappoint anybody?

609
00:30:12,350 --> 00:30:13,350
-Father-son picnic.
-My birthday.

610
00:30:13,434 --> 00:30:14,726
Our last anniversary.

611
00:30:15,728 --> 00:30:17,062
I promise.

612
00:30:24,445 --> 00:30:26,112
BILLY: Can we come over again
tomorrow night?

613
00:30:26,197 --> 00:30:27,447
-Really?
-Please?

614
00:30:27,532 --> 00:30:29,991
Yeah. What about you, Janie? You, too?

615
00:30:30,076 --> 00:30:32,160
Yeah, I guess it wouldn't be too bad.

616
00:30:32,245 --> 00:30:34,037
What do you think, buzz kill?

617
00:30:34,121 --> 00:30:36,289
A night to myself? I think I'll survive.

618
00:30:36,374 --> 00:30:38,875
Thanks, Dad. I'll see you tomorrow.

619
00:30:42,672 --> 00:30:44,756
-lt was a nice night.
-Yeah.

620
00:30:48,219 --> 00:30:50,554
-My kids want to come over.
-Who gives a rat's butt?

621
00:30:50,638 --> 00:30:52,848
Fair enough. Have a good one.

622
00:30:53,808 --> 00:30:55,600
(PENGUINS SQUAWKING)

623
00:30:58,145 --> 00:31:00,522
People love the sounds of nature.

624
00:31:00,606 --> 00:31:04,442
Helps them sleep. It's beautiful. It's natural.

625
00:31:06,320 --> 00:31:07,571
(GRUNTS)

626
00:31:08,906 --> 00:31:11,408
Excuse me. Excuse me! Hey!

627
00:31:11,492 --> 00:31:12,659
(SQUAWKING STOPS)

628
00:31:12,743 --> 00:31:14,119
Yeah. Good.

629
00:31:14,620 --> 00:31:16,663
Now shut up and go to sleep.

630
00:31:16,747 --> 00:31:19,541
Or I'll give you something to honk about.

631
00:31:21,085 --> 00:31:22,627
(ALL SQUAWKING)

632
00:31:24,463 --> 00:31:25,881
(BEEPING)

633
00:31:36,100 --> 00:31:37,309
(SIGHS)

634
00:31:44,525 --> 00:31:45,817
All right, back off.

635
00:31:45,902 --> 00:31:49,279
Spread out. Seriously.
I'm used to living alone.

636
00:31:49,363 --> 00:31:51,281
No! Expensive.

637
00:31:51,365 --> 00:31:52,574
Oh ! Ah !

638
00:31:56,454 --> 00:31:59,497
Hey, that's my remote, Pecky Peckerton.

639
00:32:00,374 --> 00:32:01,708
(TV SWITCHES ON)

640
00:32:01,792 --> 00:32:03,793
(SOUNDTRACK MUSIC PLAYING ON TV)

641
00:32:08,341 --> 00:32:09,507
Huh.

642
00:32:11,844 --> 00:32:13,345
You like that, huh?

643
00:32:13,512 --> 00:32:17,265
He's funny, right? Kind of like a penguin.

644
00:32:25,358 --> 00:32:28,360
Good. That'll loop all day.

645
00:32:31,906 --> 00:32:33,949
-I suppose it's a formal event.
-Precisely.

646
00:32:34,033 --> 00:32:35,784
Popper, where have you been?

647
00:32:35,868 --> 00:32:37,327
Hey, guys.

648
00:32:37,411 --> 00:32:38,578
We talked to Van Gundy's people.

649
00:32:38,663 --> 00:32:40,413
They say she turned you down flat.

650
00:32:40,498 --> 00:32:43,291
Fellas, calm down. Life's too short,

651
00:32:43,376 --> 00:32:44,376
especially for Franklin.

652
00:32:44,460 --> 00:32:46,252
We thought we could trust you with this.

653
00:32:46,337 --> 00:32:48,505
Hey, Taming of the Shrew
is not a one-act play.

654
00:32:49,757 --> 00:32:52,384
You know that she's
the chair of several charitable foundations.

655
00:32:52,677 --> 00:32:54,469
One of those foundations
is having a benefit

656
00:32:54,553 --> 00:32:55,804
at the Guggenheim Saturday.

657
00:32:55,888 --> 00:32:57,305
And Mr. Popper will be present.

658
00:32:57,390 --> 00:32:58,556
POPPER: I figured it out.

659
00:32:58,641 --> 00:33:01,184
She's looking for somebody
with integrity and character.

660
00:33:01,268 --> 00:33:03,061
Somebody like Jimmy Stewart.

661
00:33:03,145 --> 00:33:05,188
(IMITATING JIMMY STEWART)
And, doggone it,

662
00:33:05,272 --> 00:33:08,400
that's exactly what I'm going to be.

663
00:33:08,901 --> 00:33:10,026
I'll use my own voice, though.

664
00:33:10,111 --> 00:33:12,487
Although, that was uncanny.
Come on, give it to me.

665
00:33:12,571 --> 00:33:14,698
We expect some results, Popper.

666
00:33:14,782 --> 00:33:18,785
And until we get them, you can keep
your name off my marble slab.

667
00:33:19,787 --> 00:33:22,122
A man your age shouldn't be
talking about marble slabs.

668
00:33:22,790 --> 00:33:24,165
I got this.

669
00:33:24,625 --> 00:33:26,543
Penguins, Pippi. Talk to me.

670
00:33:26,919 --> 00:33:30,005
Per your predicament,
I printed a pertinent page from Wikipedia.

671
00:33:30,089 --> 00:33:32,132
"Gentoo penguins
may periodically imprint

672
00:33:32,216 --> 00:33:34,843
"on a particular person
as if they were a penguin.

673
00:33:34,927 --> 00:33:38,596
"Once imprinted, they remain permanently
proximate to their parental proxy."

674
00:33:38,681 --> 00:33:40,015
ls it actually written that way?

675
00:33:40,766 --> 00:33:42,017
I'm paraphrasing.

676
00:33:42,101 --> 00:33:44,310
They're imprinting, all right.

677
00:33:45,271 --> 00:33:48,857
"Uncanny tracking ability.
Can locate each other at great distance."

678
00:33:49,025 --> 00:33:51,067
-What about keeping them in line?
-Next paragraph.

679
00:33:51,277 --> 00:33:54,946
"Are more docile
when kept at lower temperatures."

680
00:33:55,448 --> 00:33:56,448
Hmm.

681
00:33:58,242 --> 00:34:01,202
Cold enough for you?
Glad you're comfortable. Ow!

682
00:34:01,287 --> 00:34:05,498
Hey! This is a finger, this is a fish.
Learn to tell the difference.

683
00:34:08,627 --> 00:34:09,711
Hey, kids.

684
00:34:09,795 --> 00:34:12,297
It's nice, huh? A little fresh air.

685
00:34:13,215 --> 00:34:14,549
It's not bad if you keep moving.

686
00:34:14,633 --> 00:34:16,551
Captain, Bitey, Stinky!

687
00:34:17,303 --> 00:34:20,138
Penguins need it cold,
otherwise they get wing mange.

688
00:34:20,639 --> 00:34:21,806
Dad, are you okay?

689
00:34:21,891 --> 00:34:24,059
Yeah. Never better.

690
00:34:24,143 --> 00:34:25,727
Let's take the penguins to the park.

691
00:34:25,811 --> 00:34:27,979
Billy, no. What if they run off?

692
00:34:28,064 --> 00:34:29,230
Ah.

693
00:34:29,982 --> 00:34:32,525
You know, maybe they are
a little cooped-up in here.

694
00:34:37,198 --> 00:34:40,075
Boy! Look at all this space.

695
00:34:40,159 --> 00:34:42,535
Makes you want to spread out and explore.

696
00:34:42,620 --> 00:34:44,329
Get lost for a while. (EXCLAIMS)

697
00:34:51,754 --> 00:34:53,338
(PIGEON COOING)

698
00:35:03,015 --> 00:35:07,018
Flight envy? Really?
(LAUGHS) That's hilarious.

699
00:35:07,103 --> 00:35:10,230
I hate to break it to you, Captain,
but those are fins.

700
00:35:10,564 --> 00:35:13,900
I think you might be more fish than fowl.

701
00:35:14,193 --> 00:35:15,610
BILLY: Hey, Dad, heads-up!

702
00:35:15,694 --> 00:35:19,656
Oh ! I see how it's going to be.
All right. Let's see what you got, Billy.

703
00:35:22,451 --> 00:35:25,370
Come on, Janie. Come on.
Let's get a game going.

704
00:35:25,830 --> 00:35:27,539
Thanks, but no thanks.

705
00:35:27,623 --> 00:35:29,332
-POPPER: Aw! Come on.
-BILLY: Let's go.

706
00:35:29,416 --> 00:35:32,418
Little Popper over to Big Popper.
Looking for the flick-on.

707
00:35:32,545 --> 00:35:33,586
Pass it. Pass it.

708
00:35:33,671 --> 00:35:37,799
Back to Little. . . Nimrod blocks it.
Over to Loudy, who dribbles it.

709
00:35:37,883 --> 00:35:38,967
-(FARTS)
-Ah !

710
00:35:39,051 --> 00:35:40,093
Flagrant flatulation.

711
00:35:40,177 --> 00:35:41,469
Could be a yellow card.

712
00:35:41,554 --> 00:35:45,890
Lovey controls, beaks it over to Billy,
who bends it like Bitey.

713
00:35:46,392 --> 00:35:49,352
Uh-oh. Better pick it up. Come on, Janie.

714
00:35:49,645 --> 00:35:52,397
What are you afraid of?
Can't beat an old man?

715
00:35:52,481 --> 00:35:56,526
"O-M-G, I'm too A-D-D to play with D-A-D.

716
00:35:56,610 --> 00:35:57,777
"Frowny face."

717
00:35:59,488 --> 00:36:00,572
(SIGHS) Fine.

718
00:36:01,448 --> 00:36:02,490
(CHUCKLES) All right!

719
00:36:03,367 --> 00:36:05,034
You know,
I heard that girls are the weaker sex.

720
00:36:05,119 --> 00:36:06,161
Didn't you hear that, Billy?

721
00:36:06,370 --> 00:36:07,829
-Yeah.
-(GROANS)

722
00:36:08,330 --> 00:36:09,789
BILLY: Are you okay?

723
00:36:18,757 --> 00:36:19,966
JANIE: Sorry, Dad.

724
00:36:20,050 --> 00:36:21,342
lt really was an accident.

725
00:36:21,427 --> 00:36:23,720
Yeah, I get it. You both have power shots.

726
00:36:23,804 --> 00:36:25,013
Mr. Popper.

727
00:36:25,097 --> 00:36:27,599
Hey, guess what? I got new contact lenses,

728
00:36:27,683 --> 00:36:29,350
i.e. , I can see more now,

729
00:36:29,435 --> 00:36:33,521
i.e. , I can still see your six illegal pets.

730
00:36:35,941 --> 00:36:38,776
POPPER: Are we cool now, Hawkeye?
Let's go, kids.

731
00:36:45,951 --> 00:36:48,077
(BILLY AND JANIE LAUGHING)

732
00:36:49,872 --> 00:36:53,082
Hey, everybody. I found him in the lobby.

733
00:36:53,292 --> 00:36:54,584
Oh, oops.

734
00:36:55,878 --> 00:36:58,129
I figured it was like
that time you lost Janie at Macy's.

735
00:36:58,214 --> 00:36:59,339
You lost me?

736
00:36:59,506 --> 00:37:00,882
You were never lost.

737
00:37:00,966 --> 00:37:03,509
I simply failed to maintain visual contact.

738
00:37:03,594 --> 00:37:05,595
lt was less than an hour.

739
00:37:08,474 --> 00:37:09,641
(JANIE LAUGHS)

740
00:37:10,726 --> 00:37:12,227
They are liking it here.

741
00:37:12,311 --> 00:37:14,771
-Do you want to keep them overnight?
-Really?

742
00:37:14,855 --> 00:37:16,064
-Yeah.
-Cool.

743
00:37:16,148 --> 00:37:18,149
And Rick and I are celebrating.

744
00:37:18,776 --> 00:37:20,944
-You got the grant.
-Yes.

745
00:37:21,028 --> 00:37:23,154
Wow. I'm really happy for you.

746
00:37:23,239 --> 00:37:24,322
-Thank you.
-(CHUCKLES)

747
00:37:24,490 --> 00:37:27,825
You know, I was planning on having them
stay at Mom's when we're in Ghana.

748
00:37:27,993 --> 00:37:31,246
You're actually going to Ghana, then.

749
00:37:31,330 --> 00:37:32,914
Just for three weeks.

750
00:37:32,998 --> 00:37:35,583
Maybe they could spend
a few nights with you.

751
00:37:35,668 --> 00:37:38,253
Hey, kids. Do you want
to stay the night with your dad?

752
00:37:38,337 --> 00:37:39,337
-Yeah.
-Sweet.

753
00:37:39,421 --> 00:37:41,256
-Okay.
-All right.

754
00:37:43,259 --> 00:37:45,593
-Good night.
-Good night, Mom.

755
00:37:45,678 --> 00:37:46,678
Good night, Mommy.

756
00:37:46,762 --> 00:37:50,765
Good night.

757
00:37:53,769 --> 00:37:55,061
(HONKING)

758
00:37:55,354 --> 00:37:56,980
You, too, Loudy.

759
00:37:58,232 --> 00:37:59,607
-Bye.
-Bye.

760
00:38:03,320 --> 00:38:04,404
You like Mom.

761
00:38:05,239 --> 00:38:06,990
I do not.

762
00:38:08,701 --> 00:38:12,036
I mean, I like her.
I don't know if she likes me.

763
00:38:12,121 --> 00:38:14,080
Does she talk about me?

764
00:38:14,498 --> 00:38:15,832
