just to find fish.

1017
00:53:02,135 --> 00:53:03,135
Hmm.

1018
00:53:03,428 --> 00:53:05,387
lt must be kind of hard on them. Huh?

1019
00:53:05,805 --> 00:53:08,432
They always get back together, though.

1020
00:53:08,975 --> 00:53:10,642
That's nice.

1021
00:53:10,727 --> 00:53:12,519
It's natural.

1022
00:53:12,604 --> 00:53:15,230
Mom, Dad wants to know
if you'll have dinner with him.

1023
00:53:15,315 --> 00:53:17,316
-What?
-Billy, I don't know if that's. . .

1024
00:53:17,400 --> 00:53:19,276
Mom, just do it.

1025
00:53:21,779 --> 00:53:22,905
What do you think of this shirt?

1026
00:53:23,615 --> 00:53:25,782
-Does it make me look pale?
-(SQUAWKING)

1027
00:53:25,867 --> 00:53:27,743
I know they are. It's a little cold in here.

1028
00:53:27,827 --> 00:53:28,869
(HONKS)

1029
00:53:28,953 --> 00:53:29,953
How dare you?

1030
00:53:30,079 --> 00:53:31,205
Oh.

1031
00:53:31,414 --> 00:53:35,250
Nice. You were going to let me
go out like that. Some friend you are.

1032
00:53:36,461 --> 00:53:38,420
I got a reservation at Jean-Georges,

1033
00:53:38,504 --> 00:53:42,549
which is almost impossible
unless you're dating The Donald.

1034
00:53:42,634 --> 00:53:44,301
Which I am not willing to do.

1035
00:53:44,552 --> 00:53:48,513
Are you guys going to be okay?
Not that I don't trust you.

1036
00:53:48,598 --> 00:53:49,973
I just worry, that's all.

1037
00:53:50,058 --> 00:53:51,475
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

1038
00:53:54,145 --> 00:53:55,270
Pipperoni.

1039
00:53:55,355 --> 00:53:57,439
PIPPI: Mr. Popper, Van Gundy phoned

1040
00:53:57,523 --> 00:53:59,524
requesting your presence
at the property in the park.

1041
00:53:59,609 --> 00:54:01,568
-Now?
-Please be punctual.

1042
00:54:01,653 --> 00:54:02,819
Okay, tell her I'll be there.

1043
00:54:04,113 --> 00:54:06,823
-I guess I'll kill two birds with one stone.
-(HONKS)

1044
00:54:08,785 --> 00:54:10,369
It's a metaphor.

1045
00:54:15,166 --> 00:54:16,291
Uh. . .

1046
00:54:16,918 --> 00:54:20,087
Yeah, we'd prefer to sit over here. Yeah.

1047
00:54:25,093 --> 00:54:26,426
Thank you.

1048
00:54:27,679 --> 00:54:28,845
Oh, thanks.

1049
00:54:32,392 --> 00:54:33,558
Are you looking for someone?

1050
00:54:33,935 --> 00:54:37,437
No. Just taking in
the ambience of the room.

1051
00:54:37,522 --> 00:54:38,772
lt hasn't changed in 30 years.

1052
00:54:38,856 --> 00:54:41,149
It's got sort of a decaying charm.

1053
00:54:46,155 --> 00:54:48,282
-Okay, what is it with that table?
-What?

1054
00:54:48,366 --> 00:54:50,200
You look like you've seen a ghost.

1055
00:54:50,285 --> 00:54:51,994
No, I'm fine.

1056
00:54:52,078 --> 00:54:54,329
Thom, it's me.

1057
00:54:57,041 --> 00:54:59,876
My dad used to bring me here
whenever he was home.

1058
00:54:59,961 --> 00:55:01,295
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

1059
00:55:01,379 --> 00:55:02,921
That was our table.

1060
00:55:03,006 --> 00:55:05,382
He used to give me these souvenirs
he'd bring

1061
00:55:05,466 --> 00:55:07,926
from his incredible adventures on the road.

1062
00:55:09,345 --> 00:55:12,514
lt was about the only time
I ever got to see him.

1063
00:55:13,641 --> 00:55:14,850
Thanks, Dad.

1064
00:55:15,935 --> 00:55:18,645
It's actually a good memory.

1065
00:55:18,730 --> 00:55:20,856
Sometimes they're the worst.

1066
00:55:22,692 --> 00:55:25,777
We were married for 15 years,

1067
00:55:25,862 --> 00:55:27,612
and you have never told me that.

1068
00:55:27,989 --> 00:55:28,989
Hmm.

1069
00:55:29,741 --> 00:55:32,367
You are a complicated man, Mr. Popper.

1070
00:55:35,246 --> 00:55:36,330
(LAUGHING)

1071
00:55:37,498 --> 00:55:39,124
I don't know.

1072
00:55:39,208 --> 00:55:40,625
I think this old place has still got it.

1073
00:55:43,671 --> 00:55:44,838
Where are we going?

1074
00:55:44,922 --> 00:55:47,382
That's for me to know
and you to find adorable.

1075
00:55:47,467 --> 00:55:48,550
Oh, really?

1076
00:55:48,634 --> 00:55:49,718
Yes.

1077
00:55:52,096 --> 00:55:53,096
(AMANDA LAUGHING)

1078
00:55:53,181 --> 00:55:56,183
POPPER: Right, left. Right, left. Right.

1079
00:55:57,101 --> 00:56:00,354
Well, we're out of the medals.
But we had a good time.

1080
00:56:00,438 --> 00:56:01,813
Nice trick.

1081
00:56:03,232 --> 00:56:06,485
I can't believe we're doing this.

1082
00:56:06,569 --> 00:56:08,904
I brought a girl here once, a long time ago.

1083
00:56:08,988 --> 00:56:11,615
lt was closed,
so we broke in and stole skates.

1084
00:56:11,741 --> 00:56:13,200
She sounds amazing.

1085
00:56:13,284 --> 00:56:14,618
I thought so.

1086
00:56:14,744 --> 00:56:19,414
Then she got on the ice,
and she was kind of a clutz.

1087
00:56:19,499 --> 00:56:21,375
I think she was just trying to impress you.

1088
00:56:21,459 --> 00:56:22,793
You remember the boathouse?

1089
00:56:22,877 --> 00:56:24,628
Oh, the boathouse.

1090
00:56:25,338 --> 00:56:28,215
-Yeah, it was surprisingly warm in there.
-Yes, it was.

1091
00:56:29,092 --> 00:56:30,801
-Yeah.
-Yep.

1092
00:56:31,094 --> 00:56:32,594
-Mmm-hmm.
-Mmm-hmm.

1093
00:56:32,720 --> 00:56:33,845
(BOTH EXCLAIMING)

1094
00:56:34,389 --> 00:56:35,472
(LAUGHING)

1095
00:56:38,101 --> 00:56:41,061
I don't know what happened there.

1096
00:56:41,145 --> 00:56:43,605
I think we just hit a rough patch.

1097
00:56:45,400 --> 00:56:46,942
I'll race you.

1098
00:56:53,783 --> 00:56:55,283
That's good, you got it.

1099
00:56:57,078 --> 00:56:58,787
Want some more? Want some more?

1100
00:56:59,497 --> 00:57:01,581
-You let him in?
-He had a badge.

1101
00:57:01,666 --> 00:57:03,792
-A badge from the zoo.
-JONES: Look at this.

1102
00:57:04,043 --> 00:57:06,253
Hey! Step away from the penguins.

1103
00:57:06,337 --> 00:57:08,463
These birds have eggs, Mr. Popper.

1104
00:57:08,548 --> 00:57:10,048
They need a full veterinary workup.

1105
00:57:10,174 --> 00:57:11,883
Yeah? Well, if I get worked up,

1106
00:57:11,968 --> 00:57:14,761
you're going to need a workup of your face.

1107
00:57:14,846 --> 00:57:16,179
Really?

1108
00:57:16,264 --> 00:57:19,307
You've got some interesting ideas
about animal care, Mr. Popper.

1109
00:57:19,392 --> 00:57:21,268
You stick them in front of the TV?

1110
00:57:21,352 --> 00:57:23,728
Yeah. Chaplin. A classic.

1111
00:57:23,813 --> 00:57:27,149
You've got one nesting
in the produce bin of your refrigerator.

1112
00:57:27,233 --> 00:57:28,316
(SCOFFS)

1113
00:57:28,401 --> 00:57:31,194
Just shows what you know.
That's a cheese drawer.

1114
00:57:31,821 --> 00:57:34,448
Fish fillet sandwich with tartar sauce?

1115
00:57:34,615 --> 00:57:36,658
ls this your idea of a healthy animal diet?

1116
00:57:36,742 --> 00:57:39,369
Ooh ! Evidence! Call CSI.

1117
00:57:40,455 --> 00:57:41,746
You planted this.

1118
00:57:41,831 --> 00:57:43,957
You have no idea
what you're doing with these birds.

1119
00:57:44,208 --> 00:57:45,542
Like you're some kind of penguin expert.

1120
00:57:47,587 --> 00:57:48,587
I am a penguin expert.

1121
00:57:49,338 --> 00:57:51,548
Yeah, but. . . Yeah, okay.

1122
00:57:52,216 --> 00:57:55,719
It's time for me to take these birds
and put them in a proper home.

1123
00:57:55,803 --> 00:57:57,387
You aren't giving them what they need.

1124
00:57:57,472 --> 00:58:00,515
I am giving them exactly what they need.

1125
00:58:00,600 --> 00:58:01,933
What? What are you giving them?

1126
00:58:02,018 --> 00:58:03,560
I am giving them love.

1127
00:58:04,103 --> 00:58:05,187
Love?

1128
00:58:05,480 --> 00:58:07,314
Well, it sounds weird
when you make me say it.

1129
00:58:07,398 --> 00:58:10,609
These aren't children, Mr. Popper.
They're animals.

1130
00:58:10,693 --> 00:58:12,486
They need food. They need snow.

1131
00:58:12,570 --> 00:58:15,489
And every once in a while,
one of them needs to be eaten by a whale.

1132
00:58:15,573 --> 00:58:16,948
-(HONKS)
-Hey!

1133
00:58:17,033 --> 00:58:18,575
You want to know who they love?

1134
00:58:18,659 --> 00:58:20,285
I'll tell you who they love.

1135
00:58:20,369 --> 00:58:22,662
Whoever is holding the fish.

1136
00:58:32,590 --> 00:58:33,840
Traitors.

1137
00:58:35,968 --> 00:58:37,010
Wake up, Popper.

1138
00:58:37,094 --> 00:58:40,347
These penguins can only survive
in the zoo or Antarctica.

1139
00:58:40,431 --> 00:58:43,558
So, sooner or later,
I will take these penguins.

1140
00:58:45,686 --> 00:58:46,770
POPPER: Omega-3s, Pip.

1141
00:58:47,104 --> 00:58:48,772
Penguins are way ahead of us on this.

1142
00:58:48,856 --> 00:58:49,981
Mr. Popper, I'm perplexed.

1143
00:58:50,066 --> 00:58:52,067
How does this pertain
to the Van Gundy problem?

1144
00:58:52,151 --> 00:58:54,819
Van Gundy? Lots of that. Lots of that.

1145
00:58:54,904 --> 00:58:56,363
Please tell me you have a plan.

1146
00:58:56,447 --> 00:58:58,573
I always have a plan, Pippi.

1147
00:59:00,243 --> 00:59:01,284
They're fresh.

1148
00:59:01,369 --> 00:59:04,746
Oh, really? Why do I smell bleach?

1149
00:59:04,830 --> 00:59:06,414
Mr. Popper,
we're being pressed for progress.

1150
00:59:06,499 --> 00:59:08,291
Perhaps I could pamper the penguins
for you.

1151
00:59:08,459 --> 00:59:10,252
You need to procure your promotion.

1152
00:59:10,336 --> 00:59:13,880
No, Pippi.
What we need is squid, and plenty of them.

1153
00:59:14,340 --> 00:59:16,925
The weather outside is frightful

1154
00:59:17,009 --> 00:59:18,802
The fire is so delightful

1155
00:59:19,470 --> 00:59:21,888
Since there's no place to go

1156
00:59:21,973 --> 00:59:25,475
Let it snow! Let it snow! Let it snow!

1157
00:59:26,185 --> 00:59:28,728
Oh ! Good morning, kids.
Babies on the way.

1158
00:59:28,813 --> 00:59:29,938
Got to get ready.

1159
00:59:31,107 --> 00:59:34,776
Young Gentoos need an ice shelf
at 28 degrees. A little powder on top.

1160
00:59:34,944 --> 00:59:37,112
That's right. I'm kind of a penguin expert.

1161
00:59:37,572 --> 00:59:38,613
Oh !

1162
00:59:39,240 --> 00:59:41,408
Hey, not in the house, young lady.

1163
00:59:41,492 --> 00:59:45,203
Besides, when you pack this stuff down,
you could really hurt somebody.

1164
00:59:45,288 --> 00:59:47,080
JANIE: Come on, let's get him, Billy!

1165
00:59:47,456 --> 00:59:48,999
(ALL LAUGHING)

1166
00:59:50,585 --> 00:59:51,668
(EXCLAIMS)

1167
00:59:55,006 --> 00:59:56,089
You're begging for it.

1168
00:59:57,550 --> 00:59:59,676
Here, hold on.
Look how much can go in this hat!

1169
00:59:59,760 --> 01:00:01,303
Look how much can go in this hat!

1170
01:00:01,387 --> 01:00:02,387
Ah !

1171
01:00:03,014 --> 01:00:04,014
Uh-oh !

1172
01:00:04,098 --> 01:00:05,307
Grab a pen, Popper.

1173
01:00:05,641 --> 01:00:08,518
I'm going to hook you up with the number
of a very good moving company.

1174
01:00:09,562 --> 01:00:10,562
Ow!

1175
01:00:14,275 --> 01:00:15,650
-Hey.
-POPPER: Wow.

1176
01:00:16,319 --> 01:00:17,694
I think I hear your mama calling.

1177
01:00:17,987 --> 01:00:20,071
(GURGLING) Kent! Kent!

1178
01:00:21,365 --> 01:00:23,950
You're only delaying the inevitable, Popper.

1179
01:00:24,035 --> 01:00:25,744
I'll be telling the board about this.

1180
01:00:25,953 --> 01:00:27,245
(FARTING)

1181
01:00:29,874 --> 01:00:33,001
POPPER: Kids, wake up.
You don't want to miss this.

1182
01:00:33,210 --> 01:00:34,878
JANIE: What are we doing?

1183
01:00:35,129 --> 01:00:36,463
Shh !

1184
01:00:41,510 --> 01:00:44,721
JANIE: Wow. Cool.

1185
01:00:52,605 --> 01:00:54,356
POPPER: Here it comes.

1186
01:00:55,232 --> 01:00:57,359
-BILLY: It's coming.
-POPPER: Look at that.

1187
01:00:57,777 --> 01:00:58,943
(CHIRPING)

1188
01:01:05,284 --> 01:01:07,160
-JANIE: Dad, look.
-Yeah.

1189
01:01:07,953 --> 01:01:10,038
-BILLY: Holy cow, another one.
-POPPER: Look, look, look.

1190
01:01:10,122 --> 01:01:11,956
It's another one.

1191
01:01:13,209 --> 01:01:15,126
POPPER: Reminds me of you guys.

1192
01:01:29,266 --> 01:01:31,893
Rangers on a breakaway!
They're out in the open ice.

1193
01:01:31,977 --> 01:01:34,312
Crosby! There's nothing but daylight!

1194
01:01:34,397 --> 01:01:36,606
-No way.
-Can Crosby back-check? Back-check!

1195
01:01:37,191 --> 01:01:39,651
-Oh ! Sorry.
-Hey, Dad.

1196
01:01:40,111 --> 01:01:42,821
-I got your number, okay?
-JANIE: Ooh ! I'm so scared.

1197
01:01:46,951 --> 01:01:48,159
POPPER: Mom.

1198
01:01:48,244 --> 01:01:50,120
The place is coming together, huh?

1199
01:01:50,204 --> 01:01:51,287
Or apart.

1200
01:01:53,207 --> 01:01:55,291
Captain's still waiting to be a dad, huh?

1201
01:01:55,376 --> 01:01:59,546
Mom. Yeah, that's right.
A woman can be a captain.

1202
01:01:59,630 --> 01:02:01,548
We don't tolerate gender bias in this house.

1203
01:02:01,632 --> 01:02:04,384
-Really?
-Cross-checking is okay, though.

1204
01:02:06,887 --> 01:02:08,471
(GROANING DRAMATICALLY)

1205
01:02:08,639 --> 01:02:10,932
-Five minutes for fighting.
-Oh, man.

1206
01:02:11,016 --> 01:02:12,642
You promise to call me when it hatches.

1207
01:02:12,727 --> 01:02:14,519
Promise. Any day now.

1208
01:02:22,903 --> 01:02:25,196
Don't worry, Captain.

1209
01:02:25,990 --> 01:02:28,408
The little fella is just taking his time.

1210
01:02:28,492 --> 01:02:29,701
And I bet he'll be a great flyer.

1211
01:02:32,913 --> 01:02:34,164
You're falling asleep.

1212
01:02:34,248 --> 01:02:35,623
No, I'm not.

1213
01:02:35,791 --> 01:02:37,709
Hmm. lt must be me.

1214
01:02:38,836 --> 01:02:40,378
You really should go to bed.

1215
01:02:40,463 --> 01:02:41,463
Uh-uh.

1216
01:02:42,047 --> 01:02:44,841
I'm not leaving him. He's a Popper.

1217
01:02:45,009 --> 01:02:46,176
(AMANDA CHUCKLES)

1218
01:02:47,595 --> 01:02:50,263
Good night.

1219
01:02:56,353 --> 01:02:57,604
(DOORBELL RINGING)

1220
01:03:02,693 --> 01:03:04,569
Oh ! Hey, guys.

1221
01:03:04,653 --> 01:03:06,112
We've left seven messages.

1222
01:03:06,197 --> 01:03:07,697
You look terrible, Popper.

1223
01:03:07,782 --> 01:03:09,115
We haven't heard anything
about the Tavern.

1224
01:03:09,200 --> 01:03:12,452
-What have you been doing?
-Uh. Well. . . Um. . .

1225
01:03:12,536 --> 01:03:15,288
I'm sure Pippi told you,
I've been kind of fighting a cold.

1226
01:03:15,372 --> 01:03:16,414
Pneumonia.

1227
01:03:16,540 --> 01:03:17,540
(COUGHS)

1228
01:03:17,625 --> 01:03:18,708
Move!

1229
01:03:20,127 --> 01:03:21,377
What the. . .

1230
01:03:21,462 --> 01:03:25,256
POPPER: If I'd have known you guys were
coming, I'd have cleaned this place up,

1231
01:03:25,341 --> 01:03:27,842
fired up the old Zamboni. (CHUCKLES)

1232
01:03:29,845 --> 01:03:32,055
The maid comes on Wednesdays.

1233
01:03:35,726 --> 01:03:37,101
He's gone insane.

1234
01:03:37,186 --> 01:03:38,186
FRANKLIN: I've seen this before.

1235
01:03:38,270 --> 01:03:40,063
This is exactly what happened
with Howard Hughes.

1236
01:03:40,689 --> 01:03:41,773
Because you're old.

1237
01:03:41,857 --> 01:03:42,857
YATES: Popper.

1238
01:03:43,067 --> 01:03:44,359
The Tavern?

1239
01:03:44,443 --> 01:03:46,110
Oh ! The Tavern.

1240
01:03:46,195 --> 01:03:48,404
The Tavern is an interesting project.

1241
01:03:49,365 --> 01:03:50,907
I have lots of ideas about the Tavern.

1242
01:03:50,991 --> 01:03:53,868
For God's sakes, man !
Pull yourself together.

1243
01:03:53,994 --> 01:03:55,954
Your house is full of penguins.

1244
01:03:56,413 --> 01:03:59,374
I know. I know.

1245
01:03:59,458 --> 01:04:00,917
I know how it looks.

1246
01:04:01,001 --> 01:04:02,460
But it's just one more egg.

1247
01:04:02,586 --> 01:04:05,046
And as soon as it hatches, I'm there.

1248
01:04:05,130 --> 01:04:07,799
Franklin, how long have I worked for you?

1249
01:04:07,883 --> 01:04:09,717
You know how many soccer games
I've skipped?

1250
01:04:09,802 --> 01:04:11,594
And dance recitals?

1251
01:04:11,679 --> 01:04:13,096
What are we doing this for, anyway?

1252
01:04:17,643 --> 01:04:19,936
There are just some things
you can't afford to miss.

1253
01:04:21,522 --> 01:04:25,191
It's too late, we've lost him.
Popper, you're fired.

1254
01:04:26,443 --> 01:04:27,652
Okay.

1255
01:04:30,614 --> 01:04:33,700
Best of luck
in your future endeavors, Popper.

1256
01:04:35,619 --> 01:04:36,661
Appreciate it.

1257
01:05:14,700 --> 01:05:17,160
POPPER: (SHIVERING)
Hatch, hatch, hatch, hatch !

1258
01:05:17,661 --> 01:05:20,079
Hatch, hatch, hatch !
Hatch, hatch, hatch !

1259
01:05:20,164 --> 01:05:24,083
Okay, it's going to happen.
I feel it. It's happening.

1260
01:05:24,168 --> 01:05:26,252
It's happening right now.
It's happening right now.

1261
01:05:26,337 --> 01:05:27,879
I'm going to give it the touch.

1262
01:05:27,963 --> 01:05:30,298
Total belief. Total faith.

1263
01:05:30,382 --> 01:05:31,633
Come on.

1264
01:05:38,015 --> 01:05:39,182
(GROANS)

1265
